"# Chapter 8 — Errors as data: introspecting failure

An error in Motoi is not a string. It is a record. Records have fields. Fields have values. Every error you have ever raised or received is queryable the same way any other value is queryable.

This chapter shows the shape of an error record, how to bind the last raised error, and how the error composes with the LLM-augmented `fix` and `pretty-error` verbs from Chapter 13.

## 8.1 The error record shape

An error record has, at minimum, these fields:

- `:message` — a human-readable string
- `:location` — where the error was raised (filename, line, column)
- `:stack` — the call stack at the time of the error, as a list of records
- `:cause` — the underlying cause if this error wraps another, or nil
- `:kind` — a symbol categorizing the error: `type-error`, `arity-error`, `unknown-verb`, `perm-denied`, etc.
- `:context` — optional metadata about what was happening when the error was raised
- `:did-you-mean` — for unknown-verb errors, a list of nearest names

Type-of on an error returns `error`:

```scheme
(type-of (last-error))
;; => error
```

Fields via projection verbs:

```scheme
(error-message (last-error))    ;; => \"unknown verb: crdr\"
(error-location (last-error))   ;; => (:filename \"repl\" :line 1 :column 2)
(error-kind (last-error))       ;; => 'unknown-verb
(error-did-you-mean (last-error)) ;; => (cdr car)
```

## 8.2 last-error — the standard binding

`(last-error)` returns the most recent error raised in the current session. If no error has been raised yet, returns nil.

```scheme
(crdr '(1 2 3))
;; error: unknown verb: crdr

(last-error)
;; => #<error:unknown-verb :message \"unknown verb: crdr\" :did-you-mean (cdr car)>
```

The error record is bound. You can introspect it, project its fields, feed it to other verbs.

## 8.3 Composing with the LLM

Chapter 13's LLM-augmented `fix` verb takes an error record and returns a suggested fix:

```scheme
(fix (last-error))
;; => (cdr '(1 2 3))
```

The LLM read the error record, saw the `:did-you-mean` field, generated a corrected form. The return is a form you can eval.

`pretty-error` takes an error record and returns a paragraph:

```scheme
(pretty-error (last-error))
;; => \"You called `crdr` but Motoi has no such verb. Did you mean `cdr` (the tail of a list)?\"
```

Both verbs work because the error is data. The LLM sees the fields; the return is human-readable prose or code.

