## 8.17 The pattern

Whenever an error surprises you, do not read the printed message. Bind and introspect.

```scheme
(some-failing-verb 42)
;; error printed

(define e (last-error))
(error-kind e)         ;; what kind
(error-message e)      ;; the raw message
(error-location e)     ;; where
(error-stack e)        ;; the call chain
(error-cause e)        ;; wrapped underlying?
(error-context e)      ;; what was happening
```

Six fields. Five verbs. Complete picture.

The printed error is a summary. The record is the full picture. When the summary does not tell you enough, introspect the record.

## 8.18 A worked example — arity mismatch

```scheme
(car)
;; error: arity mismatch — car expects 1 argument, got 0
```

Bind and introspect:

```scheme
(define e (last-error))
(error-kind e)          ;; => 'arity-error
(error-context e)       ;; => (:verb car :expected 1 :got 0)
```

The `:context` field gave you the exact expected and received arities. No parsing the message. The context is structured data.

## 8.19 A worked example — perm denied

```scheme
(card/publish 'my-cart)
;; error: perm denied — card/publish requires financial tier, caller has read tier

(define e (last-error))
(error-kind e)          ;; => 'perm-denied
(error-context e)       ;; => (:verb card/publish :required financial :caller-tier read)
```

Again, the context tells you exactly what you need to know. Two structured fields — the required tier and the caller's tier — instead of a string you would have to parse.

This is why errors as data matters. The dispatcher raises structured errors; the introspection layer reads them; the LLM composes with them. Every downstream tool benefits from the structure.

