## 8.22 A closing observation

Errors as data is one of Motoi's simpler design choices with one of the largest downstream benefits. Because errors are structured, every downstream tool — the REPL's pretty-printer, the LLM-augmented fix, the Cortex error log, the reference-manual generator — can consume them without parsing strings.

If you have used a language where errors are strings, this will feel like a downgrade at first (fewer nice colored stack traces) and an upgrade after a week (every error is queryable and composable).

Turn the page. Chapter 9 opens trace and watch.

## 8.23 A last note

The `last-error` binding is your session's error handle. It updates every time an error is raised. If you want to save an error for later, bind it explicitly:

```scheme
(some-failing-verb)
(define my-error (last-error))
```

Now `my-error` is stable — it will not change when the next error is raised. This lets you compare errors across a session, or accumulate a list of errors to analyze together.

For scripted error collection:

```scheme
(define errors '())
(define (record-error e)
  (set! errors (cons e errors)))

(for-each
  (lambda (test)
    (with-handlers ((error? record-error))
      (run-test test)))
  test-suite)
```

Every failing test's error gets captured. Now `errors` is a list of records you can introspect, filter by kind, compare, or feed to the LLM for batch analysis.

Turn the page.

## 8.24 Deep-seed — every error kind Motoi ships

Motoi's error kinds are a closed vocabulary. Every error raised by the runtime is tagged with one of these kinds. Cart authors can add their own kinds, but the base set is fixed:

- `type-error` — a value's runtime type did not match what a verb expected
- `arity-error` — wrong number of arguments to a verb
- `unknown-verb` — the verb name is not in the registry
- `unbound-variable` — the symbol has no binding in scope
- `perm-denied` — the caller does not have the required permission tier
- `rate-limit` — the verb was called too often
- `fuel-exhausted` — the evaluation exceeded its fuel budget
- `read-error` — the reader could not parse the source
- `macro-error` — the macro expander failed
- `contract-violation` — a runtime contract check failed
- `sandbox-violation` — the sandbox refused the operation
- `network-error` — an outbound network call failed
- `not-implemented` — a stub verb was called
- `user-error` — an error raised by user code via `(error ...)`
- `wrapped` — an error wrapping another error via `:cause`

Fifteen kinds. Every error you catch is one of these. Filter your error handling by kind:

```scheme
(with-handlers
  ((type-error? handle-type-error)
   (arity-error? handle-arity-error)
   (perm-denied? refuse-and-log))
  (do-the-thing))
```

The predicates (`type-error?`, `arity-error?`, etc.) are built from the error's `:kind` field. Each is one line:

```scheme
(define (type-error? e) (and (error? e) (eq? 'type-error (error-kind e))))
```

## 8.25 Deep-seed — raising your own errors

To raise an error with structured fields, use `raise-error`:

```scheme
(raise-error
  :kind 'my-error-kind
  :message \"something went wrong\"
  :context (list :user-id user-id :operation 'save))
```

The error becomes queryable via all the same field verbs. Downstream code that catches it can introspect the `:context` to know what to do about it.

Your own error kinds are just symbols. There is no registration step. Pick a symbol that describes the failure and use it.

## 8.26 Deep-seed — the guard construct

```scheme
(guard
  ((type-error? e) (display \"got a type error: \") (display (error-message e)))
  ((error? e) (display \"got some other error: \") (display (error-message e))))
  (some-code-that-might-fail))
```

The clauses are tried in order. The first predicate that matches gets to handle the error. If none match, the error propagates.

`guard` is Scheme's standard error handling construct. Motoi supports it. It composes with the introspection layer because the error value is bound in each clause.

## 8.27 Deep-seed — the :cause chain

An error can wrap another error via `:cause`:

```scheme
(raise-error
  :kind 'wrapped
  :message \"failed to save user\"
  :cause underlying-io-error)
```

The `:cause` field is another error record. You can walk the chain:

```scheme
(define (root-cause e)
  (if (error-cause e)
      (root-cause (error-cause e))
      e))

(root-cause (last-error))
;; => the deepest cause
```

This is useful when an outer verb wraps a lower-level failure with more context. You can present the outer message to the user and drill down to the root cause for debugging.

## 8.28 Deep-seed — errors and the training corpus

Every documented error in the reference manual is a training pair. The model learns: when a user sees this error, the fix is this. When a user sees that error, the fix is that.

This means errors' structured shape does double duty. It helps the human debug in real time. It also trains the model to reach for the right fix when a similar error comes up in the future.

Well-structured errors are training data. Poorly-structured errors are noise. Motoi's discipline is that every runtime-raised error is well-structured; user-raised errors are the author's responsibility.

## 8.29 A closing observation on error handling philosophy

Motoi treats errors as values that flow through the system, not as exceptions that unwind it. The traditional exception model — throw, unwind stack, catch somewhere higher — is present via `guard` and `with-handlers`, but it is not the primary story.

The primary story is: the runtime raises structured errors; the introspection layer reads them; the LLM composes with them; and the programmer at the REPL handles them by binding, introspecting, and deciding what to do.

This is a different reflex than a Java or Python programmer might have. In those languages the reflex is `try / except: log(e)`. In Motoi the reflex is `(define e (last-error)); (introspect e)`. The intent is the same — understand the failure. The path is different.

Which path is better depends on the language's shape. Motoi's shape rewards the introspection path.

Turn the page. Chapter 9 opens trace and watch.

## 8.30 One last practical pattern — error introspection at the REPL

At the REPL, the most common workflow when something errors is:

```
> (some-verb 42)
error: type error — expected number, got string

> ,doc last-error
Return the most recent error raised in the current session.

> (define e (last-error))
> (error-kind e)
type-error
> (error-context e)
(:verb some-verb :expected number :got string :arg-index 0)
```

The context field told you exactly which argument was wrong and what shape was expected. That is often the entire debug — you now know your first argument to `some-verb` was a string when it should have been a number.

This is what \"errors as data\" enables. The message would have told you a similar thing but you would have had to parse the message. The context gives you the same information as pre-parsed structured data.

Reflex time. When an error surprises you, do not read the printed message twice. Bind and introspect.

